(136, 1, '2014-08-23 01:11:23', '2014-08-22 23:11:23', 'And again, the silence rules the grand hall. The big fire was burnt down to ashes, the long tables and benches deserted. No other sound can be heard except the howling of the wind. Under the howling, Rothen thought he could hear the deep breath of the dragons. Deep and steady, just waiting for the tribe to become careless for the slightest second. He knew they were planning there revenge for the hundrous times their gold was stolen from their dangerous caves, seeking to regain their treasures, to hide and hord them under mountains and behind treacherous tunnels and dungeons.\r\n\r\nRothen was just one small mage, barely able to light a fire. But he knew about the danger for the tribe. He didn''t beliebe the head shaman who claimed the dragons to be broken once and for all time, lesser harm than fresh born puppies. The old shaman was to full of herself, not able to adept to new things. The death of two of their warriors proved that. She should let someone younger and more powerful take her place. Not that Rothen could take the ritual and hope to survive. Not only was his magic almost not existent, but he was clumsy at fighting and awkward at hunting. Once he shot an arrow and nearly hit the old shaman, since then he wasn''t allowed hunting anymore. Not that he was eager to. He loved the old valueful books about magic, even though he won''t be able to use almost all of the spells.\r\n\r\nRothen clambered out of his fell covered bed, giving up on sleep. If he was careful, he could sneak into the library and have a peek or two into the old books the shaman forbade him to read.', 'Dragontribes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dragontribes', '', '', '2014-08-23 01:11:23', '2014-08-22 23:11:23', '', 0, 'http://www.ulicor.de/blog/?p=136', 0, 'post', '', 0),
